<h3>Changing</h3>
<blockquote>
  <pre><code>$('h3').text('Javascript Libraries')
$('h3').text('Javascript Libraries').css({color: 'blue', 'font-size': '5em'})</code></pre>
<div class="alert alert-info">
  With jQuery you can chain your actions by appending them to the list. Most jQuery selector methods will return a collection of elements back so the other methods can carry on the chain.
</div>
</blockquote>

<h3>Listening</h3>
<blockquote>
  <p>jQuery can listen to various <a href="http://api.jquery.com/category/events/">events</a> and user interactions to the DOM.</p>
  <p>The most common events are:</p>
  <ul class='events-list'>
    <li>click</li>
    <li>focus</li>
    <li>mouse over</li>
    <li>mouse out</li>
    <li>hover</li>
    <li>keypress</li>
    <li>change</li>
    <li>submit</li>
  </ul>
  <pre><code>$("h3").click(function() {
  alert( "Handler for .click() called." );
});</code></pre>
</blockquote>

<h3>Animating</h3>
<blockquote>
  <p>
    The jQuery library provides several techniques for adding <a href="http://api.jquery.com/category/effects/">animation</a> to a web page. These include simple, standard animations that are frequently used, and the ability to craft sophisticated custom effects.
  </p>
  <pre><code>$(".events-list").slideUp().slideDown();
$('h3').fadeOut().fadeIn()</code></pre>
</blockquote>

